<h3 id="toc35"><span><a href="/scp-3309">SCP-3309: Where We Go When We Fade, Fade Away</a></span></h3>
<hr />
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;▷&nbsp;Learn&nbsp;more?</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p><strong>Summary:</strong> The Foundation classifies coldposts as a legitimate in-universe concept. When they learn they can <em>delete</em> these coldposts &#8212; as Wiki staff must do to their out-of-universe counterparts &#8212; they do so with extreme prejudice and imprecision. This causes everything to go wrong.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Commentary:</strong> SCP-3309 was my 4th SCP and 1st collab, co-written with <span class="printuser"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/phamtomguy" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3187915); return false;">PhamtomGuy</a></span> in April 2018. This was both my 1st format screw and 1st attempt at a meta article.</p>
<p>3309 is a bit of a strange one for me. I'm not exactly a fan of meta articles myself unless they're written competently. And I don't actually think the work I put into 3309 is enough to consider it a well-done meta article. 3309 is an ambitious story &#8212; and ambitious stories call for ambitious writing. I do believe I put in decent writing, but not enough to allow for all its parts to flow smoothly. Suffice to say: I don't think there's enough here for me to be satisfied about, but it's difficult to point out what exactly is the issue. Maybe the concept needs work; maybe it relies too much on a gimmick; maybe both.</p>
<p>Of course, as a collaborative page, there comes a point when both parties must agree to take the middle path and be happy with the work they've put in. To my co-writer, it may seem that we kept this page on the burner for long enough and that it needed to be posted, and the votes certainly seem to display a job well done. But there will always be something in me that isn't happy with the work I put in, and I guess that might never change.</p>
<p>Altogether, 3309 was a learning experience, and I hope I'm able to continue progressing as a writer.</p>
<p>(<strong>NOTE:</strong> I don't necessarily believe that votes = a decent work. 3309 was controversial &#8212; especially among site contributors &#8212; but ended up doing incredibly well).</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Themes:</strong> Depression &amp; anxiety; the fear of being forgotten; the plight of the tortured character.</p>
